# NicedayCarwash - Cursor AI Rules

## Project Overview

This is an Expo/React Native mobile application built with:
- **Platform**: Expo (managed workflow) with React Native
- **Framework**: React 19, React Native 0.81.4
- **Routing**: Expo Router (file-based routing)
- **Language**: TypeScript (strict mode)
- **Styling**: NativeWind (Tailwind CSS for React Native)
- **Backend**: Firebase
- **Linting**: ESLint with Expo config

## Project Structure

```
app/                    # File-based routes (expo-router)
├── _layout.tsx        # Root layout with theme provider
├── admin/             # Admin feature area
│   └── (tabs)/        # Admin tab navigation
└── user/              # User feature area
    └── (tabs)/        # User tab navigation
components/            # Reusable components
└── ui/                # UI components organized by feature
    └── user/          # User-facing widgets (booking, history, vehicles, etc.)
constants/             # App constants (theme, colors, fonts)
hooks/                 # Custom React hooks
assets/                # Static assets (images)
firebase/              # Firebase configuration
```

## Routing Conventions (Expo Router)

- **File-based routing**: Routes are defined by file structure in `app/` directory
- **Layout files**: Use `*_layout.tsx` naming for nested layouts
- **Route groups**: Use parentheses `(tabs)` for tab navigation groups
- **Modal screens**: Must be registered in layout files with `presentation: 'modal'`
  - Example: `app/user/add-vehicle.tsx` → registered in `app/user/_layout.tsx` as:
    ```tsx
    <Stack.Screen 
      name="add-vehicle" 
      options={{ 
        headerShown: false,
        presentation: 'modal' 
      }} 
    />
    ```
- **Route paths**: File names determine route paths (e.g., `app/user/(tabs)/home.tsx` → `/user/home`)
- **Never rename route files** without understanding navigation impact - it changes URLs

## Component Organization

- **Feature-based structure**: Organize UI components by feature in `components/ui/user/*`
  - Examples: `booking/`, `history/`, `home/`, `profile/`, `vehicles/`
- **Mirror pattern**: When adding new features, follow the existing feature-based organization
- **Reusable components**: Place shared components in `components/` root
- **Component naming**: Use PascalCase for component files and exports

## Styling Standards (NativeWind)

- **Use NativeWind**: Apply Tailwind CSS classes directly in JSX
- **Update config**: When adding new directories with Tailwind classes, update `tailwind.config.js` content paths
- **Theme support**: Use `use-color-scheme` and `use-theme-color` hooks for light/dark mode
- **Theme colors**: Defined in `constants/theme.ts` - use these for consistent theming
- **Global styles**: Import `global.css` in root layout (`app/_layout.tsx`)

## TypeScript Standards

- **Strict mode**: Always enabled - maintain type safety
- **Path aliases**: Use `@/*` for imports from project root
  - Example: `import { useColorScheme } from '@/hooks/use-color-scheme';`
- **Naming**: `forceConsistentCasingInFileNames: true` - maintain consistent casing
- **JSX mode**: Use `react-jsx` (no need for React import in JSX files)
- **Type definitions**: Place in appropriate locations, use proper TypeScript types

## Code Quality

- **ESLint**: Follow Expo ESLint config - run `npm run lint` before committing
- **Auto-fix on save**: VS Code settings configured for:
  - `source.fixAll`
  - `source.organizeImports`
  - `source.sortMembers`
- **Imports**: Organize imports properly (auto-organized on save)
- **Formatting**: Maintain consistent code style

## Development Workflow

- **Scripts** (from `package.json`):
  - `npm start` - Start Expo dev server
  - `npm run web` - Run on web
  - `npm run android` - Run on Android emulator
  - `npm run ios` - Run on iOS simulator
  - `npm run lint` - Run ESLint
  - `npm run reset-project` - Reset to blank project (use with caution)

## Safety Guidelines

- **Version management**: 
  - NEVER change Expo SDK version or React Native versions unless explicitly requested
  - Check Expo SDK compatibility when adding dependencies
- **Route naming**: 
  - Respect existing layout stacks and route names
  - Changing route file names alters URLs and navigation behavior
- **Tailwind config**: 
  - Always update `tailwind.config.js` content paths when adding new directories with Tailwind classes
- **Layout stacks**: 
  - Understand existing navigation structure before modifying layouts
  - Modal screens must be registered in appropriate layout files

## Key Files Reference

- `package.json` - Scripts and dependencies
- `app/_layout.tsx` - Global ThemeProvider, splash handling, NativeWind initialization
- `app/admin/_layout.tsx`, `app/user/_layout.tsx` - Per-area navigation stacks
- `tailwind.config.js` - NativeWind/Tailwind configuration
- `global.css` - Global Tailwind styles
- `tsconfig.json` - TypeScript configuration
- `eslint.config.js` - ESLint configuration
- `constants/theme.ts` - Theme colors and fonts
- `.github/copilot-instructions.md` - Additional detailed project documentation

## Common Patterns

### Adding a New Tab Screen
1. Create file: `app/user/(tabs)/my-screen.tsx`
2. Route automatically available at `/user/my-screen`
3. Tab navigation handled by `(tabs)` route group

### Adding a Modal Screen
1. Create file: `app/user/my-modal.tsx`
2. Register in `app/user/_layout.tsx`:
   ```tsx
   <Stack.Screen 
     name="my-modal" 
     options={{ 
       headerShown: false,
       presentation: 'modal' 
     }} 
   />
   ```

### Using Theme Colors
```tsx
import { useThemeColor } from '@/hooks/use-theme-color';
import { Colors } from '@/constants/theme';

const backgroundColor = useThemeColor({}, 'background');
```

### Using NativeWind Classes
```tsx
<View className="flex-1 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 p-4">
  <Text className="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">
    Hello World
  </Text>
</View>
```

## Best Practices

- **Component composition**: Prefer composition over complex prop drilling
- **Type safety**: Always type props, state, and function parameters
- **Error handling**: Implement proper error boundaries and error states
- **Performance**: Use React.memo, useMemo, useCallback when appropriate
- **Accessibility**: Include proper accessibility labels and roles
- **Code organization**: Keep components focused and single-purpose
- **Documentation**: Add JSDoc comments for complex functions and components

